title: For Sale:  Newport 12 ga. side by side double barrel shotgun. Double set triggers.
postcontent:
Newport side by side 12 Ga. shotgun.
 Very old turn of the century weapon.

 Shotguns of that era used a 2 9/16ths " shot shell.
 So a qualified gunsmith should be consulted to determine if modern ammunition can be used.

 What I was able to research was that all NEWPORT shotguns were made by either Crescent Fire Arm Company, Iver Johnson's Arms & Cycle Works, W. H. Davenport Arms Company or Stevens Arms & Tool Co. Again according to my research. the Model CN and Model WN were made by both Crescent and Iver Johnson.

 I f found that Aguila makes a #7 1/2 shot 1.75" 'mini' shell that will work for this gun.
 http://www.midwayusa.com/Product/255579 ... -box-of-20

 Shotgun is in good shape, no rust and appropriate patina for age.
Wood retains most of finish.
 Matching serials on forearm ( pic included )
 Forearm a touch " wobbly "

 Again, a qualified gunsmith should determine if this weapon is safe to fire and the weapon is being sold as is.

 If nothing else, it would make a great wall hanger for an antique side by side enthusiast.

 More pics upon request. I only seem to be able to load two pics on Armslist.

 Not interested in trades. Thank you.

title: For Sale:  High Standard Field King 22 LR - Two Barrels
postcontent: This is a High Standard Field King 22 LR pistol (Model FK-101) in good condition.  Year of manufacture is 1956.  The gun comes with two barrels from the factory and both are marked FIELD KING.  There is a 4 1/2 inch barrel and a great 6 3/4 inch barrel with compensator slots just aft of the muzzle.  Both barrels have bright bores with sharp rifling and good front sights.  Rear sight is adjustable.  The Field King is a relatively rare High Standard pistol and is particularly rare with the two barrel combination.  The Field King Model was only produced between 1954 and 1958.  It was made as a high quality plinker, but was too close in quality and price to the Supermatic target pistol to be viable as a separate product line.  Some of the 1954 models had a lever takedown and the remainder, including this gun, had the superior front button takedown.  The takedown is helpful in cleaning the gun and particularly helpful in making barrel swaps easy.  The only flaw of any significance to the gun I have for sale is a small chip at the bottom rear of the right hand grip.  Comes with one very good condition magazine.  I will consider partial trades for a 22 revolver such as the High Standard Double Nine, Longhorn, or Sentinel as well as H&R top break guns such as the Sportsman.  I would also consider a trade for an H&R Trapper and possibly a decent Iver Johnson or other 22 revolver.  I will also consider pump action 22 rifles.  You can contact me at REDACTED .  Of course, you must be at least 21 years old, be legally allowed to possess a firearm and have a valid Florida drivers license.

title: For Sale:  Collectable Browning SA-22 Takedown Rifle
postcontent:
Quick Sale!  $1,999

Collectable Browning SA-22 Grade II hand-engraved semi-auto takedown rifle.  Produced in Belgium in 1969 (not the post-1976 rifle produced in Japan).  The SA-22 was the first production semiautomatic .22 rifle, and is regarded as a classic firearm.  Awesome looking stock with checkering at 22 lines per inch.  The SA-22 ejects spent cases downward, which was intended by the designer to keep the user's face "protected from gasses and flying particles while firing."  Factory engraving was done by hand at FN Herstal (which is now done by laser engraving in Japan) and consists of two prairie dogs on the left side and two squirrels in a tree on the right side.  In addition there is a lone duck in flight on the top of the receiver.  The engravers initials are also included under the lone duck.  1969 Weaver C4 4-power scope is attached with a Weaver .22 Tip-Off scope mount.  Scope is super clear.  Includes original Browning case and owner’s manual.  Compare at $2,500.

title: For Sale:  Ithaca 16 Gauge SxS Flues Shotgun - Mirror Bores - Tight as a Drum - 1923
postcontent: This is an Ithaca double barrel 16 gauge Flues shotgun.  This gun is great.  Bores are mirror bright with no dark spots.  It locks up tight.  There is no slop in the breech whatsoever when it is closed.  Cocking mechanism, extractors, safety, forend assembly and everything else works exactly as it should.  Condition is good with no dents in the barrel, or rust pitting.  There is one small imperfection in the forend where it meets the rear of the iron and one small imperfection in the buttstock where it meets the receiver.  These are no larger than about 3mm and are not cracks,  They look more like places where the user was a little careless and put the gun down hard.  Both the buttstock and the forend are solid and sound.  The gun has original finish throughout and the only nonoriginal part is an early model Pachymar shoulder pad which appears to be a direct replacement for the original with no alteration to the buttstock.  This is a 1923 model which is preferable to the prewar models which are said to have weaker receivers because they were not experienced enough with smokeless powder to really know how strong the guns needed to be, but WW I taught them all the lessons they needed to know.   This gun is wonderful because it is so versatile.  The Flues models are known for being lightweight, easy to shoulder quickly and thus easy to find the target.  Trigger pull is crisp for both barrels.  Being a 16 gauge it won't kick you as hard as a twelve gauge but provides much more firepower than a 20 gauge.  16 gauge ammunition is still readily available and just as affordable as 12 or 20 at the larger sporting goods stores and at online sellers.   If you would like to purchase it and you are not in my area I will need to ship it to your FFL.  I think shipping should be $35 for a total of $385 plus whatever you have to pay to your FFL.  Still a pretty good deal for a nicer gun than the ones others are asking sort of cuckoo prices for.

title: For Sale:  Colt XM-177E1
postcontent:
The first carbine version of the M16 assault rifle appeared under the name of CAR-15 in 1965, an was intended for US Special Forces who fought in Vietnam. The original M16 was simply shortened by cutting the half of the lenght of the barrel (from original 20 inches to 10 inches) and by shortening the buttstock by another 3 inches. The butt was plastic and retractable, the handguards were of triangular shape and the flash hider was of original three-prong type. Based on the origunal CAR-15, Colt quickly developed the CAR-15 Air Force Survival Rifle, intended, as a name implied, to serve to downed airplane and helicopter pilots. This version had tubular handguards and metallick tubular buttstock, and fo some reasons the pistol grip was shortened.
Initial combat experience with CAR-15 brought up some problems. First, the carbine was too loud, deafing the firing soldier quite quickly. Second, the muzzle flash was also terrific, blinding the shooter at night and giving away the position of the shooter to the enemies. Colt partially solved this problem by installing a new, longer flash suppressor. This version, known as the Colt model 609 Commando, also carried new handguards of tubular shape. This model was officially adopted by US ARmy as XM-177E1. his version had M16A1-style receiver with forward assist button. In the mid-1967 Colt slightly upgraded the Commando by lenghting the barrel up to 11.5 inches (292 mm), and this version was adopted as XM-177E2.
